name: Rescue Mights
story:
The Skyport Arena was built to inspire awe. Tonight, it succeeded.

Fifty thousand seats rose in rings around the central floor, every one of them filled. Holographic banners rippled overhead, cycling through the blue-and-gold crest of the Vanguard program and the faces of its champions, the Rescue Mights. Spotlights carved paths through artificial fog, and the crowd's roar was a living thing, rising and falling like the breath of some great beast.

In the Prime Box, far above the chaos, the Global Hero Council watched in silence. Councilwoman Hargrove's fingers were steepled. Councilman Steele's expression was carved from granite. Director Vance hadn't blinked in three minutes. They weren't here to be entertained. They were here to judge.

And below them, in the center of it all, the Rescue Mights were putting on the performance of their lives.

"Threat cluster alpha, northwest quadrant," Ava's voice echoed through Odin's comm. "Six drones, armed. Preston, you have the angle."

"On it."

Preston moved like a freight train with a guidance system. Three drones went down in seconds, their chassis crumpling under his gauntlets with satisfying crunches. The crowd erupted.

"Beta cluster breaking east," Stella called, her shield emitter humming as she tracked the movement. "Willow—"

"Already there."

Willow's energy whip sang through the air, catching two drones mid-flight and slamming them together with enough force to scatter components across the arena floor. She landed in a crouch, grinning.

"Show-off," Preston muttered, but there was warmth in it.

Odin stood at the center of the formation, sword drawn, directing the symphony. Every movement was precise. Every call was answered. They'd run emergency simulations hundreds of times, but tonight it felt different. Tonight it mattered.

"Another wave incoming," Ava reported. "Heavy units. Odin, you're up."

The heavy drones were twice the size of the others, their armor reinforced, their weapons hot. They descended from the arena's ceiling in a V-formation, targeting systems locking onto the team.

Odin didn't hesitate.

He moved through them like water through stone, his blade finding the gaps in their armor with surgical precision. One. Two. Three. The crowd was on its feet now, chanting, screaming. Four. Five.

The last drone fell, and Odin stood alone in the center of the arena, chest heaving, sword raised.

"All threats neutralized. Civilians secured." The announcer's voice boomed through the arena.

The scoreboard lit up. Perfect marks. Zero casualties. Record time.

For one shining moment, everything was exactly as it should be.

Then the world turned to static.

---

It started with the lights—a flicker, barely noticeable. Then the holographic scoreboards glitched, the Vanguard crest dissolving into corrupted pixels. The crowd's cheers faltered, confused murmurs spreading like ripples in a pond.

"Ava?" Odin's voice was sharp. "What's happening?"

"I don't—" She was already at her wrist console, fingers flying. "Someone's in the system. I can't—"

The screens exploded with color. Not the blue-and-gold of the Vanguard. Something else. Something wrong.

A jagged, neon-red "R" tore across every display in the arena. It pulsed like a heartbeat, like a taunt, and then—

Laughter.

High-pitched. Mocking. Familiar.

"My, my, my..." The voice slithered through the sound system, amplified to ear-splitting volume. "Look at the little soldiers."

Sunrai's face appeared on the screens. He was leaning back in a pilot's chair, one leg crossed over the other, a smirk plastered across his features like he'd been born with it. Behind him, the interior of the Havoc Hawk was visible—all sharp angles and chaotic modifications.

"Sunrai." Odin's grip tightened on his sword. "What are you doing?"

"What does it look like, Mighty Boy?" Sunrai spread his arms wide, theatrical. "I'm giving the people what they really want. Entertainment."

The crowd was murmuring louder now, confusion bleeding into nervous laughter. In the Prime Box, the Council members had gone very, very still.

"See, here's the thing about your little performance tonight," Sunrai continued, his voice dripping with condescension. "It's fake. Choreographed. You're dancing through a simulation that your own school designed, and you want people to think that makes you heroes?" He laughed again. "Let me show them what the Vanguard is really made of."

The screens shifted.

At first, Odin didn't understand what he was seeing. Then he did, and his blood turned to ice.

Footage. Private footage. Training sessions that were never meant to be public.

There was Preston, tripping over a mag-lock during a midnight drill, crashing into a rack of equipment with a sound like a small explosion. The crowd laughed—hesitant at first, then louder.

There was Ava, face-down on her console after a forty-eight hour coding binge, drool pooling on her keyboard, surrounded by a fortress of empty energy drink cans. More laughter.

There was Willow, her energy whip snaring a training bot's head instead of its legs, sending the machine careening into a wall while she swore in three different languages.

Odin watched his team's faces. Preston's jaw was tight, his hands trembling. Ava had gone pale, her fingers frozen over her console. Willow looked like she wanted to murder someone, and Stella had turned away entirely, unable to watch.

But Sunrai wasn't done.

"Oh, and here's the best part." The footage cut to infographics—slick, professional, damning. The cost of the Mights' specialized gear: weapons, armor, vehicles, tech. The numbers were staggering, climbing into the millions.

And beside them, another set of numbers. The budget for the Lower Docks infrastructure repairs. The backlog of housing requests. The underfunded clinics. The crumbling schools.

"This," Sunrai said, his voice suddenly cold, "is what your 'pivotal safety net' costs. All that money, all that tech, all that training... and for what? So a bunch of kids can play pretend?"

The laughter in the crowd had died. Now there was something else. Something uglier. Doubt.

"If the Council wants real safety," Sunrai continued, leaning into the camera, "maybe they should stop hiring pampered mascots who can't even protect their own Wi-Fi." He paused, letting the words sink in. "They're not heroes. They're just expensive toys."

The screens flickered, and for one awful moment, Sunrai's face was replaced by the image of the Rescue Mights standing frozen in the arena—small, exposed, humiliated.

Then the jagged "R" returned, pulsing, triumphant.

"Ruiners out. Try not to trip on your way home, Mighty Boy."

The transmission cut. The arena lights flickered back to normal. The scoreboards returned to their default displays, but no one was looking at them.

No one was looking at the Mights like heroes anymore.

---

The silence was worse than the laughter.

Odin stood in the center of the arena, his sword still raised, frozen in a victory pose that now felt like a joke. Around him, fifty thousand people sat in uncomfortable quiet, unsure whether to applaud or jeer.

In the Prime Box, Councilwoman Hargrove had risen from her seat. Her expression wasn't angry. It was worse. It was embarrassed. For herself. For being associated with this.

Professor Brighthelm's voice crackled through Odin's private comm. "Mights. Return to staging. Now."

Odin lowered his sword. He looked at Preston, at Willow, at Stella. He looked at Ava, who was still staring at her console like she could will the last five minutes out of existence.

"We're leaving," he said quietly. "Now."

They walked off the arena floor. Not to cheers. Not to applause.

To the echo of Sunrai's laughter, still ringing in the silence.

The Ruiners hadn't just struck at the school. They had struck at the one thing the Mights couldn't armor.

Their pride.
